  "prompt": "What is the reason behind driving on the left hand side and the right hand side of the road in different countries?",
  "response": "The practice of driving on the left or right side of the road varies by country and is rooted in historical, cultural, and practical factors. Here are the key reasons behind these differences:\n\n### Historical and Cultural Influences:\n1. **Historical Traditions**:\n   - **Left-Side Driving**:\n     - Many countries that drive on the left, such as the United Kingdom, inherited the practice from medieval times. In the past, people traveled on the left to keep their right hand free to draw weapons, as most individuals were right-handed.\n     - The British Empire spread this tradition to many of its colonies, including India, Australia, and South Africa.\n   - **Right-Side Driving**:\n     - In continental Europe, the shift to right-side driving began during the French Revolution. Before this, the aristocracy drove on the left, but revolutionaries encouraged switching to the right to symbolize equality.\n     - Napoleon's influence further spread right-side driving across Europe and regions under French control.\n\n2. **Colonial Influence**:\n   - Countries colonized by the British (e.g., India, Kenya) often adopted left-side driving, while those colonized by France or Spain (e.g., the Americas) adopted right-side driving.\n\n### Practical Reasons:\n3. **Transportation Evolution**:\n   - The design of early vehicles, such as horse-drawn carriages, influenced driving customs. For example, in the U.S., drivers sat on the left side of wagons to control reins with their right hand, leading to right-side driving.\n   - The development of automobiles reinforced these practices. Henry Ford positioned the steering wheel on the left for right-side driving in the U.S., while British manufacturers placed it on the right.\n\n4. **Consistency and Trade**:\n   - Neighboring countries often adopted the same side of the road for consistency in trade and travel. For example, most European countries drive on the right, while many Asian and African countries drive on the left due to British influence.\n\n### Modern Implications:\n5. **Traffic Safety and Standards**:\n   - Switching sides of the road is expensive and disruptive, so most countries maintain their historical practices for consistency and safety.\n   - Some countries, like Sweden, have switched sides (from left to right in 1967) to align with neighboring countries and improve traffic flow.\n\nToday, about **65% of the world's population drives on the right**, while **35% drives on the left**, with left-side driving more common in countries with historical ties to the British Empire.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
